snippet.textDisplay:
I agree completely with the point made in this video that milk is good.
However, the part about animal suffering is very untrue. While there exist some farms where animals suffer, for most of the globe the milk is produced inland ( in France 96% of the milk comes from farms inside the country ) and said milk comes from farms of 60-80 cows ( which is not a lot ).
Better life conditions mean better milk so those small farms generally have good equipment, vast land for the cows to eat and warm sheleters in the cold winter.
the " cows impregnated blablabla cows killed when they no milk blablabla " really angers me. This clearly is the preconceived idea of someone who lives in a big city and never has gone ( and never will go ) to a farm. No, cows are not impregnated "over and over again". No, cows are not killed violently and brutally when they are useless and dont produce milk anymore.
First, a cow is impregated when the time is right ( aka cows is healty and cow is happy and good ) and saying a cow is " useless " is utterly stupid : while cows are cattle, they are still living beings. How can you call a living being useless ? like wtf ?
Cows are animals and treated as such. We use them and eat them, yet we treat them with care.


From a very disappointed french farm boy.

snippet.textDisplay:
@Kurzgesagt, milk is simple, if not referred to articles intended to make it controversial, non peer reviewed studies or those funded by dairy industry. Money makes it complicated.
IGF in milk is involved in all stages of cancer development. More than half of world population is lactose intolerant. Milk causes bad effects on skin quality. In India with such a large population, milk is mostly not regulated. 68% milk & milk products in India not as per FSSAI standard, most common adulterants are detergent, caustic soda, glucose, white paint and refined oil. Detergent and other contaminants like urea, starch, glucose and formalin are also used to deliberately adulterate milk as they provide thickness and preserve the milk for longer periods . The World Health Organisation (WHO) had issued an advisory to the Government of India stating that if adulteration of milk and milk products is not checked immediately, 87 per cent of citizens would be suffering from serious diseases like cancer by the year 2025.
And Kurzgesagt while concluding: "It's not harmful for the majority of the population". I am surprised no source is even cited for this one.
Why didn't you mention the downsides to the milk alternatives? Soy milk has linked to increased estrogen, which has been shown to increase the risk of prostate cancer in men.

snippet.textDisplay: The carbon footprint statistic isn’t completely true. When researchers look at carbon footprints they look at the entire process for making milk, from the trucks used to ship the milk, to the cows eating and living. However when looking at airplanes, cars, etc, they only look at the actual use of the vehicle, and don’t take into consideration the construction of those vehicles, or more importantly the harvesting and transportation of the fuel. Sure driving a car might not have as big a carbon footprint, but the shipping of gas to a gas station easily makes up for that.
snippet.textOriginal: The carbon footprint statistic isn’t completely true. When researchers look at carbon footprints they look at the entire process for making milk, from the trucks used to ship the milk, to the cows eating and living. However when looking at airplanes, cars, etc, they only look at the actual use of the vehicle, and don’t take into consideration the construction of those vehicles, or more importantly the harvesting and transportation of the fuel. Sure driving a car might not have as big a carbon footprint, but the shipping of gas to a gas station easily makes up for that.
